<HEADLINE>
FT  12 OCT 94 / Stock market points to Kohl
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW FISHER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Growing confidence among investors that Chancellor Helmut Kohl's government
would be re-elected on Sunday helped the German stock market to make further
gains yesterday after earlier concern that the coalition might lose the
vote.
The DAX index of leading stocks in Frankfurt added a further 2.3 per cent,
or 46.3 points, to reach 2,071 points after a rise of 3.3 per cent (64.2
points) on Monday. Also contributing to the continued upturn was the
stronger performance in the bond market. Despite the positive German stock
market showing, however, some economists still feel Chancellor Kohl could
have an uphill struggle to win. 'I think his chances are slightly better
than 50-50,' said Mr Holger Fahrinkrug, Frankfurt-based economist with UBS
Global Research.
This morning, he added, stock market opinion was probably tilting to a 55
per cent probability of a victory for Mr Kohl. Now, he thought, market
opinion in favour of a Kohl success had probably strengthened to 60 per
cent.
A new opinion poll yesterday gave Chancellor Kohl and his coalition partners
50 per cent. The result in the poll by the Allensbach Institute was the
coalition's best of recent weeks.
It gave the CDU/CSU 42 per cent, 0.9 points up from a week earlier, with the
FDP unchanged on 8 per cent. The SPD had slipped 0.2 points to 34.9 per
cent.
It gave the Greens 8.1 per cent, down 0.1, and the reformed communist Party
of Democratic Socialism (PDS) 3.9 per cent, down 0.6.
Recent opinion polls suggesting the governing coalition was likely to win an
outright victory have helped market sentiment.
So has confidence about the economic recovery and receding inflation,
despite yesterday's news that west German inflation in September had stuck
at 3 per cent instead of easing to an annual 2.9 per cent as provisionally
stated.
