<HEADLINE>
FT  11 OCT 94 / International Company News: Lower metal prices hit Alcoa
Australia
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRUCE JACQUES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SYDNEY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Alcoa of Australia, the integrated aluminium group, has suffered a 35 per
cent slide in net earnings for the nine months to September, reflecting the
combined effect of lower metal prices and a strengthening Australian dollar.
The company yesterday reported trading profit down to ADollars 196.4m
(USDollars 145m) from ADollars 300.4m on revenues down 8 per cent to
ADollars 1.53bn from ADollars 1.67bn. An abnormal tax gain of ADollars 59.7m
in the previous period meant that earnings available to shareholders
declined by more than 45 per cent.
Directors said that lower product prices were partially offset by higher
sales volumes of alumina and chemicals, and lower unit production costs for
most output. An exception was gold, where lower ore grades cut production
and increased costs per ounce.
The company has reacted to tighter conditions by cutting capital spending to
ADollars 82.7m from ADollars 138m and dividend payouts to ADollars 180m from
ADollars 280m in the nine months.
Alcoa's future earnings may be threatened further by a dispute with the
Victoria state government over the pricing of electric power to its Portland
smelter. The government has withdrawn some of the smelter's power supply,
but directors said yesterday that it was still operating at about 90 per
cent of capacity.
The lastest result followed a reduced tax provision of ADollars 84.3m
(ADollars 152.5m previously) and depreciation of ADollars 114.2m, compared
with ADollars 111.2m. Interest expense eased to ADollars 12.8m from ADollars
20.6m in the period.
</TEXT>
