<HEADLINE>
FT  11 OCT 94 / International Company News: MAN press distributors merge to
boost sales
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD GOURLAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Eight mainly family-owned businesses in six European countries have merged
their operations into a new company which will distribute printing equipment
across the continent for German press manufacturer MAN Roland
Druckmaschinen.
All the companies forming the new Omnigraph group in the Netherlands already
distribute MAN Roland equipment but hope to enhance their combined market
position. The new group with have annual sales of Fl 630m (Dollars 364.1m).
The Omnigraph deal, concluded at the end of last month, will provide MAN
Roland with a commonly-owned chain of distributors similar to that used by
its main competitor, Heidelberger of Germany.
The move follows the merger in The Netherlands last year of three paper
companies - KNP, Buhrman-Tetterode and VRG Group - which left the enlarged
company, KNP BT, with interests in both MAN Roland and Heidelberger
distributors.
This deal gave KNP BT an 80 per cent share of its market in Belgium and The
Netherlands. The European Commission gave the company until the end of this
year to dispose of one of its interests.
In a complex series of moves concluded by the formation of Omnigraph, KNP BT
also sold its interests in two distributors of Heidelberger equipment in
Hong Kong and South Korea earlier this year.
KNP BT will have a seat on the advisory board of Omnigraph but will play no
executive role. Omnigraph's shareholders believe the new company stands more
chance of a stock market flotation than the individual businesses on their
own.
Omnigraph hopes exposure to more markets will help it to weather the
cyclical demand for printing equipment. The company also plans to increase
sales of items like rollers, inks and plates.
Growing business, Page 14
</TEXT>
