<HEADLINE>
FT  11 OCT 94 / Insolvency case work should go to private sector, report
advises
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIM KELLY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The private sector is likely to take over much of the administrative work
required to process insolvencies as a result of a report published
yesterday.
The work is currently carried out by the Insolvency Service, a Department of
Trade and Industry agency responsible for dealing with financial failure and
tackling fraud in insolvencies.
The report to the government by accountants Stoy Hayward advocates that
administrative 'case work' be done by private sector insolvency
practitioners, leaving the Official Receivers more time for investigations.
Stoy Hayward was asked last year to study options for the privatisation of
insolvency work.
Its recommendations would open up Pounds 31m-worth of work a year to
competition between private sector licensed insolvency practitioners, many
of them members of the big six accountancy firms.
The DTI said Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, had told
officials to start preparing for implementation of the preferred option, but
no final decision had yet been taken.
While the DTI's announcement emphasised the benefits of the option for the
prevention of fraud, Stoy Hayward's detailed report did find problems with
the plan. It would result in the private sector - which would become
involved after an insolvency order was made - having a role in setting
standards and spotting fraud before handing over work to an Official
Receiver.
'If this interface does not work well the investigations of the Official
Receiver would be impaired,' says the report.
The consultants sent details of the scheme to 78 potential contractors and
42 expressed interest in undertaking work for the Official Receivers. Fees
quoted by insolvency practitioners 'may have the potential to provide
improved value for money', according to the report.
Mr Keith Ellis, a spokesman for the trade unions at the Insolvency Service,
said the option, if carried through, would cost 1,000 jobs and undermine
efforts to combat fraud.
He said case work formed a vital part in the early stages of insolvency
work.
</TEXT>
