<HEADLINE>
FT  11 OCT 94 / Ministers' deficit deal paves way for EU budget rise
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GARDNER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LUXEMBOURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
European Union finance ministers agreed yesterday on recommendations for
member states to cut their budget deficits to comply with the Maastricht
treaty terms on economic and monetary union.
The ministers, meeting in Luxembourg, also appear to have averted an EU
crisis by pressing Italy to agree on ratification of a planned increase in
the Union budget next year.
Without this increase, Spain had said it would not ratify an EU enlargement
plan to bring in Austria, Sweden, Finland and Norway in January.
Mr Kenneth Clarke, chancellor of the exchequer, resisted any suggestion that
he would be unable to make tax cuts because of the European Commission
deficit recommendations, which apply to all member states except Ireland and
Luxembourg.
With an eye on this week's Conservative party conference, he said: 'We will
make real tax cuts when we have reached a satisfactory position in public
finances.'
France won a token victory in deferring formal adoption of so-called
'excessive deficits' recommendations, after Mr Phillipe Seguin, the
anti-Maastricht Gaullist president of the National Assembly, demanded that
the European Parliament should be consulted first.
The recommendations urge member states to stick to the European monetary
union convergence plans they originally presented to their colleagues.
Italy, one of the most indebted member states, was urged to return to its
original target of stabilising its government's ratio of debt to gross
domestic product in 1995, instead of the new target of 1996 adopted by the
Berlusconi administration, in the light of economic recovery.
On the separate issue, Mr Theo Waigel, German finance minister, said he
expected the Italian opposition to the EU budget increase to be resolved
within weeks.
A senior EU official said the likely compromise would probably lower Italy's
EU fine for cheating on its milk quota of over Ecu3bn (Pounds 2.36bn) which
the Commission has sought to halve.
The UK is challenging this reduction in the European Court but, as part of
the deal, would drop its case.
</TEXT>
