<HEADLINE>
FT  11 OCT 94 / The Conservatives in Bournemouth: Rightwingers descend into
slough of despond - Fear of losing their seats will cause Eurosceptics to
keep quiet
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
This time around they will mainly avoid public confrontation. But Mr John
Major would do well not to misinterpret the relative calm of the Tory right
in Bournemouth this week.
It will not be the calm of the content. Still less of the vanquished. It
will be the calm of the despondent. And of a group that knows on which side
its bread is buttered.
Put bluntly, with the second half of the parliament now upon us rightwing
MPs, in common with the rest of the party, are starting to worry about
keeping their seats in the next general election.
With the Conservatives lagging woefully in the polls and a bright young
Labour leader threatening to make his party electable for the first time in
more than a decade, they have concluded reluctantly that the last thing the
party needs is a show of disunity. As Mr David Evans, a rightwing member of
the executive of the influential 1922 committee of Tory backbenchers, puts
it: 'The Tories like winning. They won't win if they are divided.'
Rightwingers seem as unhappy with the government's performance today as at
any time since April 1992 - although they were encouraged both by the
Eurosceptic rhetoric used by the prime minister in the European elections in
June and the promotion of two of their favourites, Mr Jonathan Aitken and Mr
Michael Portillo, in July's cabinet reshuffle.
But they fear that any immediate move to oust Mr Major could leave them
lumbered with Mr Kenneth Clarke, the incorrigibly Europhile chancellor. As
Mr Nicholas Budgen, the Eurosceptic MP for Wolverhampton South West, put it,
the right was likely to keep quiet in Bournemouth because: 'I don't think
there is any alternative.'
When they do speak out this week it will be to contribute to the debate
inside the party about how best to combat Mr Blair. They will advise against
any move to contest the centre ground that the Labour leader is attempting
to make his own. Instead, they will call on the leadership to nail its
colours to the mast in three key areas where they think it is vital to put
'clear blue water' between themselves and Labour.
The most important of these was spelt out by the Thatcherite Conservative
Way Forward in its probably vain eve-of-conference call for 2p off income
tax in next month's Budget. Even those who - like Mr John Townend, chairman
of the Tory backbench finance committee - think Mr Clarke is right not to
cut taxes until public borrowing has been reduced to acceptable levels,
still expect the chancellor to take the axe to public spending to clear a
path for tax cuts in November 1995. 'He has got to start cutting spending
this year if we are to get meaningful tax cuts before the election,' he
said.
Mr Townend also cautions against further increases in non-direct taxation.
'I think the government has underestimated the impact on the electorate of
tax increases by sleight of hand,' he said.
The right is also anxious for the government to retake the initiative on law
and order, an issue on which it thinks Labour has eroded the Conservatives'
traditional advantage, and on Europe, where it wants Mr Major to make it
clear that Britain would not join a single European currency.
With Maastricht done and dusted and the next intergovernmental conference
still more than a year away, the Tory schism over Europe looks set to be
less exposed in Bournemouth than at any Conservative conference since
Baroness Thatcher's fall. There is a potential flashpoint today in an
agriculture debate commending the government for its part in reforming the
Common Agricultural Policy. But the debate's timing, at the start of the
very first session, makes it likely that any trouble from Eurosceptics will
be on a small scale.
More worrying for the government is the right's attitude to the European own
resources bill, increasing Britain's payments to the European Union, which
is likely to come before MPs early in the next parliamentary session. Sir
Teddy Taylor is '100 per cent' certain to oppose it, notwithstanding the
feeling that the party needs to hang together at all costs. The MP for
Southend East believes the bill will be 'a massive embarrassment to
everyone' since it will increase public expenditure at a time of huge
pressure to bring spending down.
According to Sir Teddy: 'There is a depth of depression in the party I have
never seen before in 30 years. I think there is a feeling of deep gloom and
despondency. And a feeling I haven't seen since Ted Heath's time that we
hope something will turn up.'
If nothing does turn up and the party continues to trail Labour in the polls
by more than 20 points, then the main talking-point at next year's
conference in Blackpool may be the identity of Mr Major's successor.
Without some sign of tangible progress the right would by then have
concluded that if holding their tongues and avoiding public divisions was
not working, then they had better try something else. They would no longer
be prepared to 'hang on to nurse for fear of something worse'. As one
rightwinger said: 'If the Blair honeymoon doesn't end, it's better to try
anything rather than go off the precipice.'
</TEXT>
