FT  11 OCT 94 / 24 in court over London violence
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Financial Times Reporter
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Twenty-four people charged with offences arising out of Sunday's protest in
London against the criminal justice and public order bill appeared yesterday
at Highbury and Camberwell magistrates courts in London.
They were variously charged with violent disorder, affray, assaulting
police, possessing cannabis and threatening behaviour. They were remanded,
mainly on bail, for a few weeks.
Recriminations continued yesterday with police and protesters each blaming
the other for the disorder in Hyde Park and Oxford Street that led to
violent confrontations between an estimated 20,000 demonstrators and 2,000
police.
Mr Jeremy Hanley, Conservative party chairman, said yesterday that no party
had voted against the bill in the Commons. 'The vast majority of those who
demonstrated yesterday were demonstrating peacefully. It was a hard core of
very unpleasant people who decided they wanted to have violence and to break
shop windows. There is no place for them in our society.'
