FT  11 OCT 94 / The Conservatives in Bournemouth: Leaders accused of
stifling debate
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Charter Movement, a Conservative splinter group, has strongly attacked
the organisation of this year's conference in Bournemouth, accusing the
party leadership of making a determined effort to stifle debate.
Amid signs that Tory activists are divided over a large number of issues
this year - including privatisation of the Post Office and the possibility
of tax cuts - the movement said that the Tory leadership had shown
'feebleness' and 'failure' in the motions it had chosen for the conference.
The movement told delegates in a newsletter published yesterday: 'Do not
enter the conference hall burdened by commonsense. It is intended to be a
judgment-free zone.'
According to Charter the conference organisers have avoided debating a
number of issues this week which are of considerable interest to the
grassroots of the party.
'Forty-two constituencies have submitted a motion on identity cards,' the
movement says. 'But these have been completely ignored. It is clearly a
subject of intense interest, but this is no criterion when it comes to
deciding the conference agenda.'
Charter says that the subjects for this year's balloted motion - due to be
debated on Friday - have been carefully restricted. The movement says that
just 98 motions out of the 1,160 submitted by constituency associations will
be thrown into the ballot, and that these will be restricted to just six
subject headings.
It said yesterday: 'The Conservative party has become incapable of deciding
issues of debate. For so long, its conference organisers have striven to
eliminate the possibility of more than one point of view being expressed.'
</TEXT>
