<HEADLINE>
FT  11 OCT 94 / Equal opportunity policies attacked
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Equal opportunities policies which single out minority groups from the rest
of the workforce are doomed to fail, according to a study to be unveiled
later this month at the conference of Britain's main personnel organisation.
Ms Johanna Fullerton, who co-wrote the study for the Institute of Personnel
Development conference, told the magazine Personnel Today that policies
which appear to offer universal benefits for all are more successful.
Policies such as setting targets for the composition of the workforce and
positive action in recruitment advertising were the least successful,
according to the study of 285 companies. 'People seen to be given
preferential treatment doubt why they got the job, the promotion or the
training - and so do their colleagues,' said Ms Fullerton.
However, Ms Marie Cunningham, an equal opportunities adviser with British
Rail, told Personnel Today that the problem was with those implementing the
policies.
</TEXT>
