<HEADLINE>
FT  11 OCT 94 / Fall in business failures predicted
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIM KELLY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Business failures will fall by about 5 per cent in the third quarter of this
year compared with the second quarter according to Trade Indemnity, the
specialist trade credit insurer, Jim Kelly writes.
Compared with the same quarter last year the fall is predicted to be 33 per
cent. The figures are based on businesses linked to Trade Indemnity's
policyholders.
The fall in the second quarter of 1994 was 19 per cent from the first
quarter and 41 per cent from the same quarter last year. Total failures in
the second quarter were 829 compared with a predicted 785 in the third.
Mr William Simpson, chief economist with Trade Indemnity, said: 'The latest
decline in business failures supports other evidence of recuperating
corporate sector balance sheets.'
He noted, however, that house price deflation, and attempts to control
inflation in conjunction with tax increases, could combine to slow
consumption.
</TEXT>
