FT  11 OCT 94 / Changes to credit data leave City in two minds: CSO moves to
smooth data movements
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN TETT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The record consumer credit figures for August might have seemed dazzling -
but the reaction from many City economists was distinctly ambiguous. As
analysts debate the impact of the recent tax rises there is mounting
uncertainty about how far the recent credit surge points to any increase in
consumer confidence.
One reason is that the figures have proved highly volatile in recent months.
Net lending fell to Pounds 256m in May before soaring to Pounds 603m in June
then falling back to Pounds 349m in July. Levels of new lending have
fluctuated, often apparently at odds with official retail sales data.
The Central Statistical Office yesterday attempted to smooth out some of the
volatility in the new lending series by modifying its system of seasonal
adjustment. This takes account of the variation in the number of credit
processing days in a month, which can differ as a result of bank holidays
and other factors.
The move has been welcomed by groups such as the Credit Card Research Group,
an industry research body. Mr Peter Welch, head of research at the group,
yesterday said that if the CSO had not introduced the new system in August
the level of new credit-card lending would have apparently surged 11 per
cent, because August had 5 per cent more processing days than usual. Under
the new system of adjustment the figures showed credit-card lending up by
less than 1 per cent.
This move may have removed some of the statisticians' concerns, but has done
little to ease economists' broader uncertainty about what the series is
indicating.
In previous recoveries levels of lending have been regarded as a useful
barometer of consumer confidence and spending. Some economists still say
that the rise in credit this year is useful as a leading indicator of
confidence.
Mr Kevin Gardiner, UK economist at Morgan Stanley, said: 'These figures show
us that the consumer is much less worried about borrowing - and much more
confident too - than the wider world would have us believe.'
Other economists believe that this analysis seems to be at odds with other
recent retail sales data and consumer confidence surveys.
Some observers suspect that the rise in credit-card borrowing could reflect
the fact that households have not been able to pay credit-card bills as
easily after the recent tax increases.
Similarly, the increase in finance house lending might indicate that
consumers are increasingly canny in retail purchases, choosing to buy white
goods through cheap finance loans.
Mr David Owen, UK economist at Kleinwort Benson said: 'You can argue it
either way - it can either be an indicator of consumer confidence, or quite
the reverse.'
Another, more significant, factor that may also be affecting the data is
that consumers' use of credit tools appears to be shifting. Mr Welch
believes that the recent increase in credit-card lending owes more to the
increasing popularity of cards as a payment tool rather than any pick-up in
confidence.
Ms Lesley Kay, of the Finance and Leasing Association, said that the recent
surge in finance house lending might reflect the fact that 'in store' credit
is becoming more popular than bank loans or other payment tools.
As another example of the way in which finance houses may be increasing
their market share, she pointed out that the level of car loans issued
through finance houses in August grew much more rapidly than the overall
level of new registrations - a trend which is likely to please the finance
houses, but do little to help statisticians make sense of the credit
numbers.
</TEXT>
