<HEADLINE>
FT  11 OCT 94 / Commodity prices hit industry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN TETT, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The cost of materials used in manufacturing rose last month as the impact of
recent commodity price increases started to be felt. Overall, the input
price index rose by a seasonally adjusted 0.7 per cent in September, the
Central Statistical Office said yesterday.
Coffee, copper and pulp prices all rose sharply while the cost of crude oil
purchased by manufacturing fell slightly during the month.
The key reason for the coffee price rise was a world shortage which has been
aggravated by recent frosts in Brazil. The price of coffee imports has risen
by 5.3 per cent in the past month and has trebled in the past year.
The coffee price surge pushed the overall price of imported materials for
food manufacturers higher, the CSO said. Imported food manu-facturing
materials rose 2.4 per cent in September compared with August, adding 0.2
percentage points to the input price index.
This compares with a fall of 1 per cent in the month for home produced food
manufacturing products.
Rising copper prices on world commodity markets had a significant impact on
the metals sector, where input costs rose 2.4 per cent in September compared
with August, and 13.9 per cent in the year to September.
Copper prices rose 3 per cent in the month and are 30 per cent higher than a
year ago, the CSO said.
The rise in copper prices has been fuelled by stronger than expected
European economic growth and recovery in the construction industry, which
has boosted demand for the metal in the housebuilding and car industries.
Elsewhere in the index, the pulp, paper and publishing industry reported
price rises of 0.6 per cent in the month. These rises were largely passed on
to consumers, with output prices in this sector also growing by 0.6 per cent
in the month.
</TEXT>
