<HEADLINE>
FT  11 OCT 94 / Threat of Tube strikes recedes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The threat of further industrial action on the London Underground subsided
last night when the executive of the RMT transport union decided to contact
Acas, the conciliation service, and pursue its pay claim through
arbitration.
London Underground said it was considering its response to the RMT proposal.
The Underground appeared relieved that the union had not chosen new dates
for industrial action to follow last Friday's strike which partially
disrupted the Tube network.
The union has suggested that the Underground uses its own wages board, which
has both union and management representation and can arbitrate on a binding
or non-binding basis. The RMT is claiming a 4 per cent increase and has
rejected a 2.5 per cent rise accepted by five other unions representing
Underground employees.
</TEXT>
