<HEADLINE>
FT  11 OCT 94 / 'Threat' to advice bureaux
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Citizens' advice bureau services across England are under 'serious threat'
because of a central funding crisis at a time when record numbers of people
seek help with social security benefit and debt problems, the national
organisation for the bureaux said yesterday.
A four-year funding freeze imposed on the National Association of Citizens'
Advice Bureaux seems likely to disrupt core services to local bureaux across
England.
Staff fear that the national information system, on which the bureaux rely
for advice, will be hit. That would lead to patchy services when they are
most needed.
They blame officials at the Department of Trade and Industry, which has
imposed the cash standstill on the national association, which relies on the
government for 80 per cent of its funding.
Workers said the service would receive Pounds 12m for 1993-94 and the figure
would remain at that level for four years.
Ms Helena Shovelton, who chairs the association, said: 'The CAB service is
facing a serious threat. A funding standstill in reality means serious
cutbacks in services, and this is something we cannot just sit back and
accept.'
She vowed to fight for more money and added: 'It is neither reasonable nor
realistic for the government to expect the CAB service to deal with an
ever-increasing workload - much of it resulting directly from the
government's own legislative programme - without proper recognition of our
own resource needs.'
Introduction of incapacity benefit and the job-seeker's allowance, and plans
to tighten homeless legislation, were all likely to increase the workload,
she added.
</TEXT>
