<HEADLINE>
FT  11 OCT 94 / ScotRail tries to win back travellers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ScotRail, which operates most passenger trains in Scotland, yesterday
launched a series of marketing initiatives aimed at replacing revenue lost
because of the signalworkers' dispute.
Mr Chris Green, former managing director of InterCity who became managing
director of ScotRail in April, said the company's revenue from fares was
down by Pounds 8m because of the 18 days of strikes in the past three
months.
It also lost passengers because of disruption in the Haymarket area of
Edinburgh owing to a major signalling fault that took Railtrack three months
to repair. The fault caused punctuality on services from Edinburgh to
Glasgow and Fife to plummet but they have now recovered.
To win back lost passengers ScotRail has not had its usual autumn fares
increase. It is promoting a two-for-one offer running until the end of
November under which applicants obtain a free voucher for a second person if
they pay for one ticket for travel anywhere in Scotland.
ScotRail has launched an executive ticket to promote first class
accommodation on services linking Aberdeen with Edinburgh and Glasgow. The
return ticket costs Pounds 49 instead of Pounds 96.
Eight other promotions are planned to boost train travel in the winter
months.
Mr Green said the promotions would cost Pounds 250,000 but should bring
extra passengers on trains which were running anyway and incurring fixed
costs.
He said ScotRail was 'more or less on schedule' with its preparations for
the selling of its franchise by the government, which should take place late
next year.
</TEXT>
