<HEADLINE>
FT  11 OCT 94 / Russia softens stance on CSCE
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VIRGINIA MARSH and CHRYSTIA FREELAND
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BUDAPEST, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Russia yesterday appeared prepared to back down on its proposal to transform
the Conference on Security and Co-operation in Europe into the continent's
most powerful security structure.
Speaking at the opening of a two-month CSCE review conference in Budapest,
Mr Yuri Ouchakov, the head of the Russian delegation, said the CSCE should
be the 'major moving force in European security' but that there was no need
to set up a 'hierarchical system'.
Since May, Russian officials have proposed that CSCE become Europe's top
security organisation, subsuming Nato and the Commonwealth of Independent
States. The strengthened organisation would be headed by a United
Nations-style 10-nation steering committee and would mandate Nato or CIS
forces to intervene in regional conflicts.
The idea to strengthen the CSCE, which includes European and CIS countries,
the US and Canada, followed Russian concerns that its influence in Europe
was being undermined by Nato. The proposal has been rejected by the west.
Russia's back-pedalling on the CSCE comes at a time when Moscow has achieved
a quiet, though possibly temporary, victory in the creation of a post-cold
war world order. Although the west has made it clear that Russia will not be
admitted to Nato in the forseeable future, Russian objections have also put
a brake on the rapid entry to Nato of eastern European states.
Mr Sam Brown, the US delegate, said Mr Ouchakov's statement showed
flexibility on the part of the Russians and recognition that its proposals
were not possible at present. He said the US would welcome the strengthening
of the CSCE but it should remain one of a number of security structures.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>RUZ  Russia, East Europe.
    HUZ  Hungary, East Europe.
    GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9721 International Affairs.
</IN>
