<HEADLINE>
FT  11 OCT 94 / Policy fears push rouble to new low
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN THORNHILL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The rouble fell a further 6 per cent against the dollar yesterday, crashing
through the 3,000 barrier on fears of rising inflation and deteriorating
government finances.
The government reacted calmly to the fall to 3,081 from Friday's close of
2,896, and traders said there was no intervention by the central bank.
Markets are awaiting the outcome of ministerial negotiations on the Russian
budget, expected to be presented to parliament during the present session.
Mr Victor Gerashchenko, the central bank chairman, said there were still
sufficient reserves to control the currency's fluctuations, even though the
bank had spent Dollars 2bn (Pounds 1.2bn) in the past few months to support
the rouble.
But a bank spokesman yesterday blamed the rouble's fall, which has been
accelerating over the year, on speculative trading, and said reserves would
not be wasted on fruitless intervention. 'We do not want to help market
speculators,' he said.
Russia's acting finance minister, Mr Sergei Dubinin, attempting to calm
markets, said the drop was not justified by economic conditions. 'There will
be no sharp rise in inflation because objectively all money supply
indicators rule this out. There will soon be equilibrium, the market will
stabilise, inflation and the dollar rate will move in parallel,' he said.
The turmoil in the currency market will make it more difficult and expensive
for the government to raise money in the Russian Treasury bill market, which
will be much on the government's mind as it finalises the 1995 budget.
Over the weekend, ministers flew to the holiday home of Mr Victor
Chernomyrdin, the prime minister, at the Black Sea resort of Sochi to try to
settle the outstanding issues. The details of the budget will be critical
for the confidence of the currency market when they are presented to the
parliament next week.
Currency traders said the inaction of the bank and the lack of a government
policy statement were exacerbating the situation. 'We expect the devaluation
to continue - possibly to 3,300 to the dollar this week - unless some
drastic measures are taken by the government,' one trader said.
The rouble's fall is damaging the government's domestic economic credibility
as the queues lengthen outside currency exchange points and the rising price
of imported goods hurts Russian consumers. The relative stability of the
currency throughout the summer had led to a marked increase in savings and a
growing belief in a more stable economy.
Trading on the Moscow Interbank Currency Exchange, with only thin liquidity,
has proved highly volatile, with even small trades having a big impact on
the rouble's value. But the rouble's fall has been on an accelerating trend.
In July it had fallen 3.1 per cent against the dollar; in August, 4.5 per
cent; in September, 17.8 per cent; and in the first few days of October 16.5
per cent. Since the start of the year the rouble has fallen from 1,247 to
3,081 against the dollar.
Some correction to the rouble exchange rate was perhaps inevitable this
autumn, given the recent rise in the inflation rate.
The lower rouble may provide temporary relief to Russian industry and should
particularly help the energy sector, which has been badly hit by the
accumulation of inter-enterprise debts. The hard currency earnings of oil
and gas companies will now be worth considerably more when translated back
into roubles, helping to ease the sector's cash flow problems.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>RUZ  Russia, East Europe.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9311 Finance, Taxation, and Monetary Policy.
    P6231 Security and Commodity Exchanges.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
