<HEADLINE>
FT  11 OCT 94 / Berlusconi to act on report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Silvio Berlusconi, Italian prime minister, yesterday promised speedy
introduction of legislation to prevent a conflict of interest with his
ownership of Fininvest, Italy's second largest private business group. A
report by three jurists, commissioned by Mr Berlusconi in May, last weekend
recommended a special conflict of interest law. Making his first comment
since receiving the report, the premier hinted he was not entirely happy
with it. 'It seems to me the solution found is tough and inflexible, more
inflexible than in other countries,' he said.
The jurists said Mr Berlusconi could not to be forced to divest ownership of
Fininvest; but he would have to consider either voluntary divestiture or
appointment of a trustee while he held office. By committing himself to
early legislation, Mr Berlusconi appeared anxious to resolve the issue
quickly. Since gaining office five months ago, he has consistently
encountered problems created by his inability to distance himself from his
ownership of a business empire which spans television, films, publishing,
chain stores and financial services. The senate began debating the report
yesterday, as government members argued for prior agreement on the
legislation to ensure a swift passage through parliament.
