<HEADLINE>
FT  11 OCT 94 / Employers dig in over cost-cutting: German engineering
bosses pre-empt union wage demand
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By QUENTIN PEEL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BONN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Germany's engineering employers yesterday called for the planned
35-hour-week in the industry to be renegotiated as part of a package to save
jobs and cut costs.
In a pre-emptive strike on the eve of the annual wage demand from IG Metall,
the engineering workers' union, the employers served notice that
cost-cutting remains the absolute priority for the industry, still reeling
from last year's economic downturn.
The union is expected to table a claim today for a wage rise in excess of
the inflation rate, designed to compensate for real pay cuts over the past
year, and to reflect an increase in productivity forecast at more than 3 per
cent.
The employers' move to renegotiate the 35-hour week, the most hard-fought
achievement of the engineering workers in recent years, seems certain to
infuriate the union leaders, who were forced to accept a virtual pay freeze
for their members last year.
But Mr Hans-Joachim Gottschol, the president of Gesamtmetall, the
engineering employers' federation, warned yesterday: 'The shortening of the
working week limits the room for any wage increase.' He added that the
planned 35-hour week, due to come into effect from October 1, 1995, should
be renegotiated as part of a package aimed at more flexible working
practices, and an overall cut in costs.
Mr Gottschol said that the wave of redundancies through the engineering
industry, which was running at 30,000 a month last year, had finally halted,
not least thanks to the job security deal involved in last year's pay
settlement. That deal allowed individual employers to put their staff on to
short-time working without full compensation in their pay packets, as an
alternative to outright redundancies.
His five-point plan includes an extension of the current deal on short-time
working and job security, cost-cutting, renegotiating the 35-hour week,
negotiating a special deal to employ the long-term unemployed, and seeking
more flexibility in the wage package to give relief to small and
medium-sized enterprises.
The number of short-time workers in the industry has now sunk from 750,000
at the low point of the recession in 1993 to 80,000 today, Mr Gottschol
said. He forecast a growth rate of 3 to 4 per cent in the electrical and
mechanical engineering industry as a whole in 1994, but warned that the
effects of the recovery were very patchy.
Since mid-1991, 750,000 jobs had been lost in the west German engineering
industry because of the pressure of costs, and the loss of orders.
</TEXT>
<XX>
