<HEADLINE>
FT  11 OCT 94 / Rise in raw material prices fuels UK fears of inflation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN TETT, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The cost of raw materials used by British manufacturers rose significantly
last month as the surge in world commodity prices pushed up the expense of
imported materials.
The rise fuelled fears that there could be price pressures in the pipeline
which might increase the UK's currently low inflation rate.
The cost of goods leaving factory gates last month rose at a relatively
subdued rate, suggesting that many companies are still being forced to
absorb the rising costs.
The Central Statistical Office said yesterday that the price of goods
purchased by manufacturing industry rose by a seasonally adjusted 0.7 per
cent last month and by 5.7 per cent in the 12 months to September.
The rise was larger than the City had expected. In August the annual growth
rate was 3.9 per cent.
The cost of goods leaving factory gates increased by 0.2 per cent in
September, however. Measured without the volatile elements of food,
beverages, tobacco and petroleum, output price inflation grew by a
seasonally adjusted 0.4 per cent in September and by 2.1 per cent over the
12 months.
The prices of imported materials, especially commodities such as coffee and
copper, rose particularly sharply. Consequently, the sharpest price
increases were reported in manufacturing sectors with greater exposure to
world commodity prices, such as the pulp and paper, metals, rubbers and
chemicals sectors.
The Treasury said yesterday that the underlying inflation trends remained
very benign.
'This is a sharp price increase, but it is from a pretty low level,' it
said. In addition, any rise in material costs should be partly offset by the
fact that unit wage costs - the key component of business costs  - had
fallen slightly.
Nevertheless, City economists yesterday pointed out that last month's rise
had come after several months of increases in output costs.
Some analysts suggested that this indicated companies were increasingly
seeking to pass on the recent price increases.
Others argued that customer resistance to price increases remained strong
and warned that the recent surge in commodity prices might squeeze corporate
margins in those sectors that were highly commodity dependent.
Changes to credit data leave City in two minds, Page 10
Financial market opinion influenced rate rise, Page 10
Lex, Page 20
Bonds, Page 30
London stocks, Page 42
</TEXT>
<XX>
