<HEADLINE>
FT  11 OCT 94 / Lucas shares climb despite Pounds 214m restructuring costs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BOLGER and PAUL CHEESERIGHT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Extensive restructuring by Lucas Industries is to cost the UK automotive and
aerospace components group a total of Pounds 214m in exceptional charges,
double previous forecasts.
Shares in Lucas, however, rose yesterday by 17p to 194p as the City reacted
positively to the new strategic direction outlined by Mr George Simpson, who
took over as chief executive of the Birmingham-based company in June.
Mr Simpson, former chairman of Rover Group, is focusing on three areas -
automotive, aerospace and electronics. One aim is to shorten response times
and improve service levels to increasingly demanding manufacturers.
He also announced the planned disposal of two aerospace businesses in the US
 -Lucas Communications and Electronics and Lucas Aviation, which between
them employ 550 people.
Mr Simpson said: 'It is quite clear that three of our core business areas
must be restructured if they are to achieve a competitive edge and maximise
their contribution to future earnings.'
Job losses at the group - which during the financial year cut its workforce
by 3,200 to 45,700 - would be 'hundreds rather than thousands', he said.
The provisions led to a pre-tax loss of Pounds 129.7m for the year to July
31, compared with profits of Pounds 49.5m last time. Operating profit rose
by 40 per cent to Pounds 84.2m. Sales were flat at Pounds 2.6bn but,
excluding divestments, grew by 7 per cent.
Sir Anthony Gill, chairman, was confident the progress already demonstrated
in underlying performance would be maintained, so the final dividend had
been held at 4.9p to give an unchanged total of 7p.
The biggest chunk of provisions was the Pounds 94.3m writedown of goodwill
on businesses earmarked for sale, which has no effect on shareholders'
funds. Another Pounds 87.6m covers the future costs of restructuring and
anticipated costs of settling legal claims in the US, where the group has
been accused of failing to fulfil government defence contracts.
Mr Simpson said: 'It is important to note that less than 40 per cent of such
provisions have a direct cash implication and this will be, in the main,
offset by planned divestment proceeds.'
