<HEADLINE>
FT  10 OCT 94 / International Company News: Aker warns of lower full-year
earnings
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN FOSSLI
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   OSLO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Aker, the Norwegian oil and gas technology and cement and building materials
group, has announced weaker results for the first eight months of the year
and warned of a lower annual profit.
Group pre-tax profit slipped to NKr358m (Dollars 53.45m) from NKr526m as
sales dipped to NKr11bn from NKr11.9bn. Operating profit fell to NKr441m
from NKr518m. The result was in line with analysts' expectations, however.
The decline was due to a lower activity in oil and gas technology -
particularly by Norwegian Contractors (NC) and Aker Engineering - which will
post a significantly lower result in 1994. Aker also warned of weaker
offshore activities in 1995.
NC faces a substantial reduction in business due to changes in market
conditions and will cut the number of its employees to 300 in 1995 from
2,000.
Domestic and international cement and building materials markets are
experiencing growth - after a four-year lull - which will improve the
division's 1994 result.
'Even though the upturn is modest, this has a significant impact on profits
as a result of restructuring and cost-efficiency measures undertaken by Aker
in recent years,' it explained.
The cement and building materials division achieved sales of NKr4.16bn
against NKr3.91bn as pre-tax profit rose to NKr211m from NKr191m. Aker
expects the improvement to continue.
The oil and gas technology division's sales fell to NKr6.39bn from NKr7.48bn
as pre-tax profit declined to NKr156m from NKr343m.
At the end of the eight-month period, the division's order book stood at
NKr6.4bn, down from NKr10bn at the end of 1993, due to lower activity in the
domestic offshore sector and postponement of several new development
projects.
NC, which builds concrete oil and gas platforms for the offshore sector, saw
eight-month sales fall sharply to NKr2.1bn from NKr3bn and plunged into a
pre-tax loss of NKr5m from a profit of NKr160m.
</TEXT>
